   357→## FAQ
   358→
   359→<details><summary>Should I commit my `.env` file?</summary><br/>
   579→## Docs
   580→
   581→Dotenv exposes four functions:
   587→### Config
   588→
   589→`config` will read your `.env` file, parse the contents, assign it to
   590→[`process.env`](https://nodejs.org/docs/latest/api/process.html#process_process_env),
   591→and return an Object with a `parsed` key containing the loaded content or an `error` key if it failed.
   605→#### Options
   606→
   607→##### path
   608→
   609→Default: `path.resolve(process.cwd(), '.env')`
   625→##### quiet
   626→
   627→Default: `false`
   648→##### encoding
   649→
   650→Default: `utf8`
   658→##### debug
   659→
   660→Default: `false`
   668→##### override
   669→
   670→Default: `false`
   678→##### processEnv
   679→
   680→Default: `process.env`
   692→### Parse
   693→
   694→The engine which parses the contents of your file containing environment
   695→variables is available to use. It accepts a String or Buffer and will return
   696→an Object with the parsed keys and values.
   705→#### Options
   706→
   707→##### debug
   708→
   709→Default: `false`
   721→### Populate
   722→
   723→The engine which populates the contents of your .env file to `process.env` is available for use. It accepts a target, a source, and options. This is useful for power users who want to supply their own objects.
   748→#### options
   749→
   750→##### Debug
   751→
   752→Default: `false`
   756→##### override
   757→
   758→Default: `false`
   764→## CHANGELOG
   765→
   766→See [CHANGELOG.md](CHANGELOG.md)
   770→## Who's using dotenv?
   771→
   772→[These npm modules depend on it.](https://www.npmjs.com/browse/depended/dotenv)
